Course description

Understanding user psychology can revolutionize UX design. You don't need a psychology degree to see that people behave in predictable patterns. Many psychological studies offer insights invaluable for designers. For example, in the famous "Gorilla Experiment," viewers watching a video of students passing a basketball often fail to notice a person in a gorilla suit. This shows how people can miss obvious changes when focused on a task. For designers, it highlights the need for clear and intuitive interfaces that guide users' attention effectively.

In Uxcel's UX Design Psychology course, we'll explore why one negative experience can be a deal-breaker and how to avoid cognitive biases. You'll learn why the optimal number of menu options isn't seven and what Miller's Law actually says about human memory.
We'll dive into three key psychological needs that drive user engagement and why understanding user memory is crucial.

The course covers the importance of empathy, trust-building strategies like free trials, and the pitfalls of deceptive patterns.

Finally, you'll discover how small details, like a progress tracker or positive reinforcement messages, can significantly enhance user engagement and satisfaction. This course offers a comprehensive guide to creating user-centered, psychologically informed designs.

What youll learn with UX Design Psychology

  • Understand psychological user needs

    Gain insights into what drives user behavior and create designs that truly resonate with users.

  • Avoid common design pitfalls

    Identify and prevent common UX mistakes by understanding cognitive biases and user memory limitations.

  • Build long-term user trust

    Learn effective strategies to foster user trust and loyalty through thoughtful design choices.

  • Optimize cognitive load

    Understand how to manage cognitive load to create interfaces that are intuitive, efficient, and user-friendly.
